         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">H. B. M. ¶  Consulate, Canton, ¶ 14. Sept. 1878. ¶ My dear Baron von Mueller, ¶  ¶ A perusal of the original and independent classification of Grasses in the "Flora Australiensis" ¶  has caused me to ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">78.09.14</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Henry Hance</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSSS M1, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS found with a specimen of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Chamaeraphis</seg> (MEL 248420). MS annotation by M: 'Answ Febr. 79'. Letter not found.</p>
               </note>H. B. M.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Her Britannic Majesty's.</p>
               </note> Consulate, Canton,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">14. Sept. 1878.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Baron von Mueller,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A perusal of the original and independent classification of Grasses in the "Flora Australiensis"<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham (1863-78), vol. 7, pp. 419-670.</p>
               </note> has caused me to go back to one of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">mes premiers amours</hi>
               </seg>, in the shape of a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Chamae</hi>
               </seg>rha<seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">phis</hi>
               </seg> on which I wrote a notice ten years ago. (Seem. Journ. Bot, VI, 109.)<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Hance (1868), where the genus is given as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Chamaeraphis</seg>, the more usual spelling.</p>
               </note> Though some of Bentham's changes — such as the removal of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Isachne">Isachne</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg> &amp; <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Coelachne">Coelachne</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg> from the neighbourhood of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Panicum">Panicum</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg> (your <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Micraira">Micraira</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg> I do not know), seem to me rather startling, yet I was truly glad to find that he retained <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Chamaerhaphis</hi>
               </seg> as a genus. <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Panicum">Panicum</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>, indeed, as it stands in Steudel,<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Steudel (1855), part 1, pp. 37-99. </p>
               </note> is such an unwieldy aggregate of very diverse species, that I have always felt a sympathy with the views of Grisebach, as given in the "Flora rossica" of Ledebour,<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Ledebour (1842-52), vol. 4, p. 324, at the opening of the discussion of the grasses, cites a MS of Grisebach dated 1852.</p>
               </note> who I believe was more disposed to dismember it than anyone else; but the question is how really <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">stable</hi>
               </seg> characters can be found for these groups. When I first sent our grass to Kew, I supposed it might be <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">C. aspera</hi>
               </seg>, N. ab E.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">i.e. C. G. D. Nees von Esenbeck, whose name for the species is recorded in Wallich (1828-49), specimen no. 8679.</p>
               </note> (of which at the time I had no specns. at all), and it also seemed quite certainly Griffith's <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Pseudorhaphis</hi>
               </seg>
               <note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Pseudoraphis</seg>?</p>
               </note>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Brunoniana</hi>
               </seg>, figured in his Icones pl. asiat. iii. t. 145.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Griffith (1847-54), part 3, fig. i of plate 145, and the associated text in Griffith (1847-54a), part 3, p. 29.</p>
               </note> Both Bentham &amp; Munro, however, were inclined to refer the Chinese grass to <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">C. hordeacea</hi>
               </seg>, R. Br., whilst Munro said Griffith's was = <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">C. depauperata</hi>
               </seg>, N. ab E.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Unpublished comments to Hance, reported in Hance (1868), p. 110.</p>
               </note> It seems impossible that at Kew, where the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">reliquiae Griffithianae</hi>
               </seg> were distributed, there could be any mistake as to the plant he intended; and yet it is incontestable that his figure is very unlike authentic specimens of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">C. depauperata</hi>
               </seg>, and exactly like our Canton ones! Now, however, it appears that Bentham could not at that time have known <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">C. hordeacea</hi>
               </seg>, of which it would seem there are no specns. in Europe, except those originally gathered by Rob. Brown.<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Robert Brown (1773-1858) collected in Australia, 1801-05. </p>
               </note> So that things are altogether "a good deal mixed", as they say in the United States. I see that Bentham reduces <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">C. aspera</hi>
               </seg> to <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">C. spinescens</hi>
               </seg>, Poir., a name cited by no previous author, and now considers the Chinese plant, — contrary to his former decision, — to belong here.<note xml:id="ftn12" type="footnote" n="12">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham (1863-78), vol 7, p. 498. </p>
               </note> I am one of those who have never had any leaning to the system of wholesale reduction in favour at Kew, often depending entirely on theoretical considerations, though I know you too are inclined to follow in the same direction; but my objection certainly does not arise from any abstract preference for analysis, for I quite concur with the general views followed out in the 'Genera plantarum.' Without knowing the Australian <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">C. spinescens</hi>
               </seg>, I still remain most distinctly of opinion that the Chinese grass is as different from <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">C. aspera</hi>
               </seg> as from <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">C. depauperata</hi>
               </seg>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Very good specimens of our species have been again met with last spring, and I send you now a supply of these, with a request that, if you can possibly spare me a named specn. of each of your different Australian forms, you will kindly do so. I have another from Arracan<note xml:id="ftn13" type="footnote" n="13">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Arakan? A <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>British imperial administrative division, on the eastern seaboard of the Bay of Bengal, now part of Myanmar.</p>
               </note> — which, if not new, may be the same as Brown's <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Panicum%20abortivum">Panicum abortivum</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your genera <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Xerochloa">Xerochloa</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>, <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Amphipogon">Amphipogon</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>, <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Potamophila">Potamophila</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>, <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Heterachne">Heterachne</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>, <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Diplopogon">Diplopogon</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>, and <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Cetrosia">Cetrosia</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>
               <note xml:id="ftn14" type="footnote" n="14">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Hance clearly wrote '<name key="Cetrosia">Cetrosia</name>', but this was almost certainly a transposition error for <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Ectrosia</seg>.</p>
                  <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
               </note> are all unknown to me.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I do hope we may get Munro's Rvision of all Grasses in a year or two.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">I am,</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>My dear Baron,</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Very sincerely yours,</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>H. F. Hance.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
